<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Target Oregon's Willamette Valley for Maximum Value</strong> - Skip expensive Burgundy and focus on Oregon producers like A to Z Wineworks ($18), Erath ($16), or King Estate ($19). These wines offer authentic Pinot Noir character with bright cherry fruit and earthy undertones at a fraction of the cost. The volcanic Jory soil creates wines with natural acidity that age gracefully for 3-5 years.</li>

  <li><strong>Seek Out Entry-Level Wines from Premium Producers</strong> - Look for second labels or regional bottlings from respected houses like Louis Jadot's "Couvent des Jacobins" ($19) or Domaine Drouhin's Oregon Pinot Noir ($18). These wines benefit from the same winemaking expertise as their flagship bottles but use fruit from younger vines or less prestigious vineyard sites.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at Proper Cellar Temperature (60-62°F)</strong> - Unlike expensive Burgundy that can handle slightly warmer serving temperatures, budget Pinot Noirs under $20 show best when served cooler. This temperature preserves their delicate fruit character and prevents the alcohol (often 13.5-14.5%) from becoming too prominent. Remove from refrigerator 20-30 minutes before serving.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip the Decanter for Most Under-$20 Bottles</strong> - Most affordable Pinot Noirs are made for immediate consumption and don't require decanting. However, if you find a bottle that seems tight or overly tannic (like some Russian River Valley selections), a simple swirl in your glass for 10-15 minutes will provide sufficient aeration without over-exposing the delicate aromatics.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Burgundy-Style Glasses, Not Bordeaux Bowls</strong> - The wide bowl and narrow rim of a proper Burgundy glass concentrates the subtle red fruit and earth aromas that define good Pinot Noir. Avoid large Bordeaux glasses which can make lighter-bodied wines under $20 seem thin and diluted. A 16-20 oz Burgundy glass is ideal.</li>

